and the hparams you mentioned may not be that critical in this sense. sn9 is not a good example, their lb is almost frozen all the time and it doesn't matter whether the allowed registration is high or not. in contrast, a too-fast registration in a more dynamic sn like us and sn6 may cause a slower convergence of vtrust.

"product of values" vs "sum of values". interesting.

``` 
Impact on norm_score
Product (np.prod):
The result will be significantly influenced by any zero or very small values because multiplying by zero results in zero and multiplying by a small number results in a smaller product.
Useful in situations where the combination of factors needs to account for all individual contributions being significant. If any value is zero, the final product is zero, indicating a failure in at least one component.

Sum (np.sum):
The result is a straightforward addition of values, which can be more robust to individual zero or small values as they don't nullify the entire score.
Useful when each factor contributes additively to the final score, providing a cumulative measure of the factors.
```
